title: dirigible
body:
A type of [[aircraft]], usually cigar-shaped, that floats by means of a large balloon, usually filled with hydrogen or helium.

There are three types of dirigibles:

* [b]Blimps[/b] have a non-rigid airframe; its shape is maintained by the pressure of the gas within.
* [b]Zeppelins[/b] have a rigid airframe which holds its shape even when uninflated. Zeppelins are named after their pioneer, Ferdinand von Zeppelin.
* [b]Semi-rigid[/b], a hybrid of the other two.

On Danbooru, [[dirigible]] refers to real life floating aircraft; for fantasy airships, see [[airship]].

title: synthesizer
body:
An electronic device that produces a variety of sounds. A synthesizer typically offers a preset range of different "patches", but as distinct from other types of portable keyboard instruments, it also allows the user to heavily edit the parameters of these sounds or even import/create entirely new sounds. As such, one almost always finds a densely populated control panel in addition to pitch and modulation wheels (see Yamaha, Kurzweil, Clavia Nord) or combination X-Y joystick (see Roland, Korg).

The common synthesizer has a keyboard similar to that of a piano, leading it to be sometimes called [[keyboard_(instrument)|keyboard]].

title: hoegaarden
body:
Hoegaarden (pronounced “who garden”) is a Belgian witbier named after a small town in the Flemish region of Belgium that is famous for the rebirth of the Belgian white (“wit”) style of beer. During the 1950s Tomsin, the last white beer brewery in Hoegaarden, closed. The local milkman, Pierre Celis, had worked at the Tomsin brewery as a young man. In 1965, while in his forties, Celis decided to purchase some brewing equipment and start making white beer again. He recreated the recipe based on his experience working at the brewery and from locals who remembered the look and taste of the beer. His new brewery was called De Kluis, meaning “cloister,” in honor of the monks who brewed beer in the region during the Middle Ages. The beer was called Hoegaarden, after Celis’ hometown.

Sold in dozens of countries worldwide, Hoegaarden is widely considered the standard of the Belgian-white style of beer. It is made from malted barley, unmalted wheat, hops, coriander, and curaçao orange peel. It is very pale in color and hazy with a frothy head of foam. The aroma and taste are citrusy, fruity, spicy, and refreshing, with a light snappy bitterness. The beer is light-bodied, well balanced, and mild in strength and balanced with a deceptively mild amount of alcohol (4.9% ABV).

Hoegaarden quickly became successful in Belgium and elsewhere around the world. By 1985 the brewery was producing 75,000 hectoliters of beer per year, when disaster struck and the brewery burned to the ground. Unable to rebuild on his own, Celis turned to the Belgian brewing group Interbrew (now AB-InBev), who eventually ended up owning the brewery and brand.

Types of Hoegaarden beer.

Rosée.
Launched in 2007, 3% ABV. Available in the Benelux.

Citron.
Launched in 2008, 3% ABV.

Grand Cru.
Launched in 1985, 8.5% ABV.

Julius.
An 8.8% blonde ale, with a dry taste formed through triple-hopping.

Forbidden fruit.
(French: Fruit Defendu. Flemish: Verboden Vrucht) An 8.5% dark ale, with complex spicing.

Spéciale.
Launched in 1995, 5.7% ABV. Hoegaarden Spéciale is a full-bodied, rich Belgian-style wheat beer, available from October to January.

title: kamado_tanjirou
body:
Main character from [[Kimetsu no Yaiba]].
He is a Demon Slayer in the Demon Slayer Corps, who joined to find a remedy to turn his sister,  [[Kamado Nezuko]], back into a human and to hunt down and kill demons, and later swore to defeat [[Kibutsuji Muzan]], the King of Demons, in order to prevent others from suffering the same fate as him.

Before he became a Demon Slayer, Tanjiro was a coal burner before his entire family was slaughtered by Muzan while his younger sister, Nezuko, was turned into a demon.

He has ruffled, [[black hair]] with burgundy tips, combed back to expose his forehead, and wide, dark [[red eyes]] with [[white pupils]] that appear lighter around the lower section of his irises.

Tanjiro first appears wearing a checkered, black and sea foam green [[haori]] over a white robe and black pants. He occasionally sports a [[turquoise scarf]] and is seen with circular, [[white bands]] looped around his calves. He also wears a distinct pair of [[hanafuda earrings]], with the image of the rising sun over a mountain.

During the Final Selection, Tanjiro wears a blue, cloud-patterned samue-styled [[kimono]] and [[black pants]], nearly identical to Sakonji's outfit. He still wears his [[hanafuda earrings]], but his hair is cut extremely short and remains the same length since. Similar to the rest of the apprentices that were trained under Sakonji, Tanjiro wears a hand-carved [[fox mask]] crafted from his master on the left side of his head. The mask has red accents on the eyes, ears, and spots on each corner of its mouth. On the upper right corner of the mask, there is a sun-shaped design that likely symbolizes the scar on his forehead.

After becoming a Demon Slayer, Tanjiro wears the standard [[Demon Slayer uniform]], a dark-brown gakuran jacket, a white belt, baggy chocho zubon pants that extend into tabi socks, a pair of zōri with red straps, and bands of white cloth wrapped tightly around his calves resembling kyahan, all beneath his signature [[checkered haori]]. He carries a large [[wooden box]] on his back (which was a gift to him from [[Urokodaki Sakonji]]), where his sister sleeps as they travel during the day.

[spoiler]After being turned into a [[demon]] by [[Kibutsuji Muzan]], Tanjiro is able to heal the growth on his face as well as regenerate his lost arm and other smaller injuries. He obtains eyes with [[slit pupils]], fangs and flame-shaped marks over his left forehead and right jaw that are reminiscent of those of [[Kokushibou]], in addition to a third, smaller flame-shaped mark coming down from the right side of his head down to his eyebrow after he conquered the weakness to sunlight. His scar turns into a flame-pattern as if it were a permanent Demon Slayer Mark, has become longer and is the largest of the three, and all three marks vaguely point towards his nose, though only his scar-mark reaches it. He still dons his bloodstained corps uniform, one sleeve ripped off where his arm was severed, but loses his checkered haori and the Nichirin Sword at his hip.[/spoiler]

[spoiler]After returning to his human form, Tanjiro loses the ability to see from his right eye, the iris of which is now a dull pink-gray color and the pupil black rather than its original white. His left arm, which he regrew as a [[Demon]], now takes the appearance of that which an older person may have, becoming wrinkled and skeletal, and he loses all feeling in it below the elbow and thus the ability to move it from his forearm down.[/spoiler]

h4. External Links
* "Kimetsu no Yaiba Wiki: Tanjiro Kamado":https://kimetsu-no-yaiba.fandom.com/wiki/Tanjiro_Kamado

body:
Charlotte "Shirley" E. Yeager (シャーロット・E・イェーガー, Shārotto E Iēgā?) is a witch of the [[501st Joint Fighter Wing]]. She originates from [[Liberion]]. Possibly in reference to model and photographer Bunny Yeager, Charlotte's familiar is the [[rabbit]].

Magnanimous in character, tall and buxom in appearance, Charlotte ("Shirley" to her friends) is a thrill-seeker who is fascinated by speed. Concerned with cleanliness, Charlotte had her personal bath transported all the way to the [[Strike Witches]]' [[Britannia]] base when she was transferred from the Liberion Army 363rd Fighter Wing. She is strong, confident and sociable. She is good friends with [[Francesca Lucchini]]. She has an orange plane named Glamorous Shirley.

She is based on "Chuck Yeager":http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chuck_yeager, and shares many characteristics with her archetype: Yeager was the first pilot to travel faster than sound in 1947, and would later break further speed and altitude records in his life; he was a mechanic, similar to Shirley's tinkering, and flew a plane he named the Glamorous Glennis.

title: su-100y
body:
A Soviet prototype self-propelled gun, developed during World War II but never put into production.  It was a variant of the (also canceled) [[T-100]] heavy tank that had a 130mm naval gun in a fixed casement, and was intended to destroy bunkers.  Only one prototype was ever built, and the record is uncertain as to whether it was ever used in combat.

With its distinctive flat-armored, rectangular fighting compartment, the SU-100Y has acquired the affectionate nickname "Box Tank" among players of video games that feature it as a playable vehicle (a convention that started with players of the online multiplayer battle game [i]World of Tanks[/i], in which it is included as a tank destroyer despite the fact that that was not its actual function).

The real SU-100Y prototype still exists, in the collection of the Kubinka Tank Museum in Russia.

title: aa_megami-sama
body:
[b]Aa! Megami-sama[/b] (ああっ女神さまっ, [i]Oh My Goddess![/i] or [i]Ah! My Goddess![/i]) is a Japanese seinen manga series.

The series follows college sophomore [[Morisato Keiichi]] and the goddess [[Belldandy]] who moves in with him in a Buddhist temple; after Belldandy's sisters [[Urd (aa megami-sama)|]] and [[Skuld (aa megami-sama)|]] move in with them, they encounter gods, demons and other supernatural entities as Keiichi develops his relationship with Belldandy.

The series is written and illustrated by [[Fujishima Kousuke]] and has been serialized in [i]Monthly Afternoon[/i] since September 1988; the individual chapters are being published in tankōbon by [[Kodansha]], with the first released on August 23, 1989; the final volume of the manga series, volume 48, was released on July 23, 2014, marking nearly 26 years of publication.

Aside from the manga, the series is also known for the two main anime adaptations: the 1993 OVA, and the later 2005 anime series that spanned two seasons. These are the most popular versions of the series, especially outside of Japan (where the manga remained the most popular iteration of the series). Other media include the 2000 movie, a series of short comedy episodes, a second OVA (consisting of three episodes), and a special called "Fighting Wings" that adapts the story arc of the same name from the manga.

[b][i]Contra Hard Corps[/i][/b], released in Japan as [b][i]Contra: The Hard Corps[/i][/b] (魂斗羅 ザ・ハードコア), is the first and only [[Contra]] game for the [[Sega Mega Drive|Sega Mega Drive/Genesis]] released by [[Konami]] in 1994. 

Technically pronounced "core", but more fun to pronounce "corpse". The game was also released in Europe and Australia as [[Probotector]].

It is set five years after the events of [[Contra III The Alien Wars]] released for the [[Super Famicom]] some years before. 

Is notable because of its high level of difficulty, several playable characters and multiple player-choice paths and endings, as well as its non-stop action. 

This game amazed many players when it showed [[video game]] special effects nobody ever thought the Mega-Drive/Sega Genesis hardware could even produce in that system...

title: hand_warmer
body:
A device that generates heat and is used to keep the hands warm.  These devices can be disposable or reusable and they produce heat through various means, such as chemical reaction, burning fuel, or using electricity.

Disposable hand warmers are a simple sealed pouch filled with material that undergoes a chemical reaction that produces heat.  Reusable hand warmers commonly produce heat either through the combustion of a fuel, as is the case with charcoal or lighter fluid hand warmers, or using electricity through a heating coil, as is the case for battery hand warmers.

A device similar to a disposable hand warmer that has been designed to adhere to the bottom of a sock is referred to as a [[toe warmer]].

title: lounge_chair
body:
A type of outdoor furniture that allows a sunbather to [[reclining|recline]] in a relaxed position. Often found at a [[beach]] or at [[poolside]], possibly in conjunction with a [[parasol]]. Also known as a sun lounger, chaise lounge (US), or deck chair (UK).

They serve a similar purpose as a deck chair, though a deck chair is a type of folding chair (with a fabric or vinyl strip that forms the seat and backrest, e.g. post #1159067) and the shapes are reversed. A sun lounger has a longer seat than back, while a deck chair has a longer back than seat.

title: karate
body:
[b]Karate[/b] (空手) is a [[martial arts|martial art]] developed in the Ryukyu Kingdom. It developed from the indigenous Ryukyuan martial arts (called [i]te[/i] (手), "hand"; [i]tii[/i] in Okinawan) under the influence of [[china|Chinese]] martial arts, particularly Fujian White Crane. Karate is now predominantly a striking art using punching, kicking, knee strikes, elbow strikes and open-hand techniques such as knife-hands, spear-hands, and palm-heel strikes. Historically, and in some modern styles, grappling, throws, joint locks, restraints, and vital-point strikes are also taught. A karate practitioner is called a [i]karateka[/i] (空手家).

title: ohtsuki_yui
body:
An [[Idolmaster Cinderella Girls]] character in the Passion (Yellow Sun) category.

Yui is a playful, laid back and informal 17-year-old girl who marches to the beat of her own drum. Initially her love of candy was played up as her primary quirk; it faded into a minor trait as her character developed. She became best friends with [[Aikawa Chinatsu]] after befriending her at the game's first New Year's event. In fact, one of her stages of evolution leading up to a swimsuit S Rare features her wearing Chinatsu's glasses.

She has been known to tease the Producer about indirect kisses when she offered him a lick of her lollipop, which is her favorite food. She refers to the Producer with the “-chan” honorific.

In the tie in Cinderella Girls Theater skits, Yui is a fun loving and excitable teen. She loves the freedom some roles give her, particularly that of a pirate. She tries to be mature by bringing her version of a hot drink to an onsen, but finds the cola to be disgusting due to it having gone flat. She is friends with Chinatsu and [[Mary Cochran]]. She wanted to walk with the Producer under an umbrella together and tried to get a taste of [[Mochizuki Hijiri]]’s cake until Hijiri began to cry in worry for a sugar figurine’s life. Yui is quick to point out that [[Ohta Yuu]]’s chocolate figure is suspicious and hopes Akky isn’t in any danger.

Due to her popularity, she was selected for the 9th set of CINDERELLA MASTER CD series, alongside [[Igarashi Kyoko]], [[Ninomiya Asuka]], [[Nakano Yuka]], and [[Aiba Yumi]]. She is voiced by [[Yamashita Nanami]].

title: nakano_yuka
body:
Character from [i][[Idolmaster Cinderella Girls]][/i]. Has brown eyes and long black hair in twintails.

Yuka is a karate champion who seeks to expand her horizons by becoming an idol. She was her karate teams’ team captain and was the ranking National Champion. Karate is a major aspect of her life, but she wants to be a master of dance and song as well.

Interestingly, unlike other idols' hobbies, Yuka’s is never visually incorporated into her idol costumes. She's shown to wear a karate gi in her first card illustration (taken before she became an idol), but it's never been shown on stage. In the tie in Cinderella Girls Theater skits, Yuka is depicted as being abnormally strong. In her first appearance, she breaks a dartboard in half with a single throw. She has some experience with cooking, although she does have trouble keeping up with a pumped up [[Mukai Takumi]]. She participated in a talk battle with [[Hamaguchi Ayame]], [[Ohnuma Kurumi]], and [[Hayami Kanade]]. When she landed a role with [[Yamato Aki]] and [[Manabe Itsuki]] in a Kung Fu movie, she eagerly performed moves that had a focus on animal names. She seems to like [[Mizumoto Yukari]]’s sleeping face.

Due to her popularity, she was selected for the 9th set of CINDERELLA MASTER CD series, alongside [[Ninomiya Asuka]], [[Ohtsuki Yui]], [[Igarashi Kyoko]], and [[Aiba Yumi]]. She is voiced by [[Shimoji Shino]] [下地 紫野].

title: koutetsu_teikoku
body:
[b]Steel Empire[/b] (originally released as [i]Koutetsu Teikoku[/i] (鋼鉄帝国) in Japan, and otherwise known in various English materials as [b]The Steel Empire[/b] or [b]Empire of Steel[/b]) is a side-scrolling shoot 'em up [[video game]] released on the Sega Genesis / [[Sega Mega Drive]] home consoles in 1992, and was later ported to the Nintendo [[Game Boy Advance]] in 2004 and to the [[Nintendo 3DS]] in 2014.

Steel Empire is notable amongst shoot 'em up games for its unique aesthetic designs. Mostly low-tech in nature, with its being set in the late-19th century of an alternate world, the game's aircraft, weaponry, powerups, environments, enemies and bosses are heavily stylized adding strong [[steampunk]] elements to the style, themes and visuals of the game. Steam power, propeller-based aircraft, biplanes, dirigibles and heavily armored steam trains with giant cannons play large roles in the game's protagonists and opponents.

title: figure_four_leglock
body:
The wrestler stands over the opponent who is lying on the mat face up and grasps a leg of the opponent. The wrestler then does a spinning toe hold and grasps the other leg, crossing them into a "4" (hence the name) as he does so and falls to the mat, applying pressure to the opponent's crossed legs with his own. 

While the hold applies pressure to the knee, it actually can be very painful to the shin of the victim. While the move is primarily a submission move, if the opponent has his shoulders on the mat, the referee can make a three count for a pinfall. If the referee is distracted, heel wrestlers may grab onto the ropes while executing the move to gain leverage and inflict more pain. 

With enough strength and willpower, the wrestler on defense can flip himself (and also their opponent) over onto their belly, which is said to reverse the pressure to the one who initially had the hold locked in.

This is innovated by "Nature Boy" Buddy Rogers and popularized by Ric Flair. Flair's daughter, [[WWE]] superstar [[Charlotte Flair]], uses a bridging variation which she calls the [i]Figure-Eight Leglock[/i].

body:
The main character of the game [[off (game)|OFF]]. His skin is entirely [[white_skin|white]], and he wears an old [[baseball uniform]], with a black [[baseball_cap|cap]] sometimes hiding his eyes, and fights with a metallic [[baseball_bat|bat]]. Some character interpretations depict him as having [[extra_eyes|four eyes]]. His hair is not shown, but it's supposed he has black hair.

Is often followed by floating circles, referencing his ingame add-ons and referred to as his "Party", and strongly opposes ghosts. His goal is the purification of the world.

[spoiler]
It's eventually revealed that his "purification" is essentially the end of the world, as every area that he cleansed is left white and empty, with only a few exceptions, leaving demons behind but killing almost all the population.
It's also revealed that he's not human, and it's explained he acts out of free will.
By the end of the game, the player gets the choice to support the Batter in his last fight or to betray him, causing the Batter's appearance to change from an emotionless man to a giant humanoid abomination with a elongated mouth. This form is known as "Bad Batter."
[/spoiler]

Due to his actions, he's sometimes associated with [[chara (undertale)|Chara]] from [i][[Undertale]][/i], even if he has different reasons, seeing his actions as a mercy killing, compared to Chara's sadistic tendencies.

title: h6k
body:
[b]H6K[/b], or [b]Kawanishi H6K[/b], was a flying boat produced by the Kawanishi Aircraft Company and used during World War II for maritime patrol duties by Imperial Japanese Navy. The Allied reporting name for the type was [b]Mavis[/b]; the Navy designation was "[b]Type 97 Large Flying Boat[/b]" (九七式大型飛行艇).

The aircraft was designed in response to a Navy requirement of 1934 for a long-range flying boat and incorporated knowledge gleaned by a Kawanishi team that visited the Short Brothers factory in the UK.

H6Ks were deployed from 1938 onwards, first seeing service in the Sino-Japanese War and were in widespread use by the time the full-scale Pacific War erupted, in December 1941. At that time of the war, four [i]Kōkūtai[/i] (air groups) operated a total of 66 H6K4s.

The type had some success over South East Asia and the South West Pacific. H6Ks had excellent endurance, being able to undertake 24-hour patrols, and were often used for long-range reconnaissance and bombing missions. From bases in the Dutch East Indies, they were able to undertake missions over a large portion of Australia.

However, the H6K became vulnerable to a newer generation of more heavily armed and faster fighters. It continued in service throughout the war, in areas where the risk of interception was low. In front-line service, it was replaced by the Kawanishi H8K.

title: kimura_lock
body:
Kimura (Brazilian Jiu-Jitsu), chicken wing/double wristlock ([[wrestling]]), or reverse keylock are terms used to specify a medial keylock known in [[judo]] as gyaku ude-garami (reverse arm entanglement) or simply as ude-garami. 

The application is similar to the americana, except that it is reversed. It needs some space behind the opponent to be effective, and can be applied from the side control or guard. Contrary to the americana, the opponent's wrist is grabbed with the hand on the same side, and the opposite arm is put behind the opponent's arm, again grabbing the attacker's wrist and forming a figure-four. By controlling the opponent's body and cranking the arm away from the attacker, pressure is put on the shoulder joint, and depending on the angle, also the elbow joint (in some variations the opponent's arm is brought behind their back, resulting in a finishing position resembling that of the hammerlock).

The kimura was named after the judoka Kimura Masahiko, who used it to defeat one of the founders of Brazilian Jiu-Jitsu, Hélio Gracie. It is then popularized in pro wrestling by [[WWE]] wrestler [[Brock Lesnar]], where he would use it often to break his opponent's arm, in storyline.

title: leon_s._kennedy
body:
One of the main characters of the [[Resident Evil]] series, debuting in [[Resident Evil 2]].

[b]Leon Scott Kennedy[/b] is a rookie cop assigned in Raccoon Police Department (R.P.D.). In 1998, Leon would later meet [[Claire Redfield]] and arrive together in Raccoon City. Realizing the chaos brought by the outbreak, the two became separated and arrive at the city's police station to seek shelter. The two arrived at the precinct for their own purposes as they find for possible ways to escape the city as the station was also swarmed by the undead.

After the events of Raccoon City, Leon departs and was apprehended by the US military, eventually becoming a STRATCOM agent alongside with a fellow agent, [[Jack Krauser]].

h4.Appearance
Leon is a tall man with [[blonde hair|blonde]] or [[brown hair|brown]] hair in a [[curtained hair|curtained fashion]] and [[blue eyes]]. His appearance varies throughout the series.

* [b]Resident Evil 2[/b]: Leon wears a [[police uniform]] with [[blue shirt]], [[blue pants]], [[elbow pads]], [[fingerless gloves]], and black boots. In the 1998 version, Leon wears a police uniform containing [[shoulder pads]] and a [[body armor]] with the "R.P.D." logo imprinted on it. In the 2019 remake, Leon wears a more modern uniform, now containing numerous [[pouch|pouches]] and a [[knee pads|knee pad]]. The R.P.D.'s  patch is also imprinted on the blue shirt.
* [b]Resident Evil 4[/b]: Leon has a [[brown jacket]] along with a [[black shirt]], [[fingerless gloves]], [[black pants]], and a pair of [[black footwear|black shoes]]. After losing his jacket, a [[holster]] can be seen wrapped around his torso.
* [b]Resident Evil: The Darkside Chronicles[/b]: During the events of Operation: Javier, Leon wears a similar outfit to the ones he wore in [i]Resident Evil 4[/i], albeit he sports a [[green pants]] with a [[camouflage]] pattern and lacks a jacket.
* [b]Resident Evil 6[/b]: Leon has a much more matured appearance in [i]Resident Evil 6[/i], he sports a [[leather jacket|black leather jacket]] along with [[black shirt]], [[white pants]], and black shoes.

He is a childhood acquaintance of [[moritaka (housamo)|Inuzuka Shino Moritaka]] with a rather world-weary disposition. When he works as part of the Invaders, he acts in operations devised by Inumura Daikaku Masanori and is specially charged with infiltrating other guilds and attacking their VIPs. He has a self-sacrificial personality who chooses to do the dirty work himself. Yoshito prefers masters who treat him not as a person with feelings, but as a tool. Here in Tokyo, Yoshito fights with a giant robot body his guildmaster has given him. This robot is able to install the past memories of others. If Yoshito were to use it in conjunction with his Sacred Artifact, he could conceivably copy and recreate the techniques of the other Hakkenshi. He has a very thin attachment to life and strongly believes himself to be replaceable. Yoshito apparently shows sympathy akin to pity when it comes to people who do not have a definite singular sense of self. In contrast, he tends to avoid those with high self-esteem and those who pride themselves as the one true ancestor or originator.

title: pyrrha_nikos
body:
Pyrrha Nikos is a character from [[RWBY]], a Rooster Teeth production. Her design is inspired by Achilles. 

Pyrrha is the "P" in Team JNPR. She is friendly, thoughtful, and self-sacrificing. Nicknamed the "Invincible Girl" by the public for her prodigal skill in student combat tournaments.

[spoiler]
She is killed near the end of volume 3 by Cinder Fall with the remains of her weapons gear and armor recovered and then melted down and incorporated into Jaune Arc's sword and shield and armor in the 6 month time-skip between volume 3 and 4 as a memento of her to him.  
[/spoiler]


h4. Abilities

Pyrrha wields [[milo_and_akouo|Miló]] and [[milo_and_akouo|Akoúo̱]]. Miló is a weapon with three forms: a [[javelin (spear)|]] [[spear]], a [[xiphos_(sword)|xiphos]] (small [[sword]]), or a [[rifle]]. It is red with bronze trimming. Akoúo̱ is a bronze metal rounded [[shield]] often worn as a [[buckler]]. 

Her weapons are also her emblem (a shield and spear). Pyrrha's semblance is "polarity" (control over magnetism), which helps her fight with her weapons (especially when throwing her shield) and subtly influence the moves of her opponents. 

h4. Physical Characteristics 

Pyrrha has [[green eyes]] and [[long_hair|long]] [[red hair]] tied in a [[ponytail]]. 

She stands 6 feet tall when wearing her usual heels. 

h4. Attire 

Pyrrha usually wears a metal headpiece (a [[circlet]] or [[forehead protector]]) around her head. Two small emeralds hang from the metal band on delicate chain loops near her ears. 

Her combat attire includes a bronze [[gorget]] around her neck, [[black_gloves|black]] (or very dark red/brown) [[elbow gloves]], a bronze metal [[armlet]] on her upper left arm, a bronze metal [[vambraces|vambrace]] secured with black cross-laces on her lower left arm (to which her shield attaches), a brown leather or dark bronze [[breastplate]] which resembles a [[corset]] secured with black cross-laces in the back, a red [[sarong]] over a dark red or [[black_skirt|black]] [[miniskirt]] (with possibly another pair of black shorts underneath), a [[buckle|buckled]] [[belt]] with circular metal plate bearing her emblem on the right and two [[belt_pouch|belt pouches]] hanging off the back, bronze metal [[leg armor]] ([[greaves]]) reaching up to mid-thigh (possibly [[zettai ryouiki]]) over dark red/brown/black thighhighs, and dark brown leather [[high heel boots]] with bronze trim. 

In school, she trades her combat outfit for the usual Beacon Academy [[school uniform|uniform]] ([[white shirt|white]] [[blouse]] with red [[neck ribbon]], brown [[blazer]], and [[plaid skirt]]), but keeps her bronze metal headpiece. 

h4. External links

title: hajimete_no_otsukai
body:
The first errand ([i]hajimete no otsukai[/i]) refers to the first time children are sent on an errand by themselves, usually to buy groceries at the local store, and is a fairly common milestone for families in Japan. It was also the subject of a non-regular, documentary/reality television series broadcasted by [[Nippon TV]] (available on Netflix since April 2022 under the title "Old Enough!") 

Common elements in images include dragging a [[grocery bag]] with items spilling out, [[crying]], [[lost child|getting lost]] and [[carrying]] siblings. Occasionally there will be an older family member discreetly lurking nearby. Images with this tag do not need to be the [i]literal[/i] first time a character goes on an errand.
